  1. (8pt) Compute the average LE growth from 1960-2019 across the continents. Show the results in the order of growth. Explain what do you see. Hint: these data (data in long form) is not the simplest to compute growth. But you may want to check out the lag() function. And do not forget to group data by continent when using lag(), otherwise your results will be messed up! See https://faculty.washington. edu/otoomet/info201-book/dplyr.html#dplyr-helpers-compute.
df %>%
  filter(time == 1960 | time == 2019,
         !is.na(region)) %>%
  group_by(region, time) %>%
  summarize(mean_le = mean(lifeExpectancy, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  mutate(dif = mean_le - lag(mean_le)) %>%
  filter(!is.na(dif)) %>%
  select(region, dif) %>%
  arrange(desc(dif)) %>%
  print()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'region'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.

7. (6pt) What was the ranking of US in terms of life expectancy in 1960 and in 2019? (When counting from top.) Hint: check out the function rank()! Hint2: 17 for 1960.

df %>% 
  filter(time == 1960 | time == 2019) %>%
  filter(!is.na(name)) %>%
  group_by(time) %>%
  mutate(rank = rank(desc(lifeExpectancy))) %>%
  filter(iso3 == "USA") %>%
  select(time, lifeExpectancy, rank, name) %>%
  print()
## # A tibble: 2  4
## # Groups:   time [2]
##    time lifeExpectancy  rank name                    
##   <dbl>          <dbl> <dbl> <chr>                   
## 1  1960           69.8    17 United States of America
## 2  2019           78.8    46 United States of America
  1. (6pt) If you did this correctly, then you noticed that US ranking has been falling quite a bit. But we also have more countries in 2019what about the relative rank divided by the corresponding number of countries that have LE data in the corresponding year? Hint: 0.0904 for 1960.
num_countries <- df %>% 
  filter(!is.na(lifeExpectancy)) %>%
  filter(!is.na(name)) %>%
  group_by(time) %>%
  summarise(n_countries = n())

us_rank <- df %>% 
  filter(!is.na(name) & !is.na(lifeExpectancy)) %>%
  group_by(time) %>%
  mutate(rank = rank(desc(lifeExpectancy))) %>%
  filter(iso3 == "USA") %>%
  select(time, rank)

result <- left_join(num_countries, us_rank, by = "time") %>%
  mutate(rel_rank = rank / n_countries)

result
